(# How To Build Codex Agents) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Last updated: April 21, 2026) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 1\) What you are building) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(A Codex agent is a task runner that can:) Tj
T*
(- read your repo context,) Tj
T*
(- follow local rules \(`AGENTS.md`, policies, runbooks\),) Tj
T*
(- use tools \(shell, MCP connectors, web when needed\),) Tj
T*
(- and implement scoped engineering work safely.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(There are two practical build tracks:) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(1. In-repo Codex agent workflow \(best for engineering execution\)) Tj
T*
(2. App-level API agent workflow \(best for product features in your app\)) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(## 2\) Fast path: in-repo Codex agent workflow) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### Step A: Define agent behavior in repo policy files) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Create or maintain:) Tj
T*
(- `AGENTS.md` for coding rules, validation commands, and guardrails) Tj
T*
(- mission docs \(for example: `program.md`, `CHANGE_POLICY.md`\)) Tj
T*
(- validator scripts your agent can run every cycle) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Goal: make expectations explicit so the agent executes consistently.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### Step B: Add reusable capabilities via skills) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Use skills for specialized workflows \(example: Supabase, docs lookup, image generation\).) Tj
T*
(Keep each skill focused:) Tj
T*
(- trigger conditions) Tj
T*
(- exact run steps) Tj
T*
(- fallback behavior) Tj
T*
(- constraints) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Goal: reduce prompt repetition and improve reliability.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### Step C: Add MCP connectors for external systems) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Use MCP when the agent needs structured access to platforms \(docs, GitHub, Canva, etc.\).) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Typical setup command pattern:) Tj
T*
(- `codex mcp add <name> --url <server-url>`) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(Goal: avoid brittle scraping and give the agent typed tool calls.) Tj
T*
() Tj
T*
(### Step D: Use the right runtime mode) Tj
T*
ET
endstream
